Bad Posture at contact? Pulling off the ball? Here’s how to fix it ⬇️⬇️⬇️

• Every good swing has balance between rotation and direction. Some hitters become more rotational than directional leading to pulling off the ball and bad posture at contact. Here’s some things that helped me fix these issues.

• My mental cues to fix this was to think about taking my back shoulder to and through the baseball. Like I was using my back shoulder to cut the ball in half. Level, to it, and through it with my back shoulder. I know what you’re thinking..”pulling off is a front shoulder thing not a back shoulder thing” true, but for me personally when I focused on these mental cues with my back shoulder it fixed the pull off and bad posture at contact allowing me to stay through the ball and create more backspin.

Here are my go to drills to help with these adjustments:

1. No peek drill: a pretty simple drill here, take an object and place it five feet in front of home plate. After you make contact keep your head down on that object and feel your chin on the back shoulder in your finish. 

2. Step through drill: one of my all time favorites to get more directional. Take a swing, finish your swing regularly, and take a step through towards the pitchers mound. If the step is difficult to take it’s a sign that your direction is off and you’re probably pulling off. If the step is easy and you flow right into it then your direction is good and there is no pull off happening.

3. 45° closed drill: the point of this drill is to go no low half and really isolate the upper half. This drill forces good direction and extension to get good results. If you can lace a line drive up the middle while closed off at 45° then your direction is good. If you’re top spinning or hooking balls then you’re pulling off.

Good posture = good extension = good backspin. Backspin = BOMBS 💣 Give these drills a try to nix pulling off the ball and get that posture and direction right 👍🏼

#hitting #hittingdrills #hittingcoach #hittingpost #baseball

Body first. Hands last. Barrel whips through the zone. 

Does my knob face the ball at some point? Sure it does. Does my knob push to the ball? No it doesn’t. 

To clarify my knob to ball post, every hitters knob faces the ball at some point but I think hitters who push the knob to the ball before the hips fully turn are missing out on serious barrel control and power. Agree or disagree that’s what I believe is best for hitters and I only believe this because I tried knob to ball at the pro level and failed miserably with it.no way to adjust to elite pitching with a handsy swing. Do I believe this is the only way to be a successful hitter? No. Tony Gwynn and Derek Jeter we’re hall of famers who played their whole career leading with the hands in their swing, those are elite hitters with elite hand eye and elite hands, and still they used their body very well. I do not think most young hitters should learn to hit that way. Every hitter is different, and every hitter has things that work for them and things that don’t. As a hitting coach I will teach my hitters out of the bad habits that brought me failure at the pro level so they don’t have to hit those walls in their career 👍🏼

#hitting #hittingdrills #hittingcoach #hittingpost #hittingmechanics

SEPARATION is a must! 

Primary Separation: Create the stretch = more time & space for your swing.

Secondary Separation: Hip Shoulder Separation = Adjustability & Power. Gets the barrel in the zone early. This can be a fairly rotational move so be careful that your upper half doesn’t become too spinny. Still need to maintain direction after contact!! 

#hitting #hittingdrills #hittingcoach #hittingpost #hittingmechanics

HUNT YOUR STRENGTHS‼️

• Let’s talk about the importance of hunting your strengths at the plate. Being the typical lefty that I am my strength was always the low and inside fastball, a pitch I felt confident about attacking and driving. As a young hitter I developed the ability to hit the ball to all parts of the field which all young hitters need before they can hunt a specific strength of theirs.

• Why hunt a certain part of the zone? Is it important to have the ability to cover all parts of the zone? YES. But if I go up to the plate with the plan to cover all parts of the zone I may be more defensive than offensive with my swings. When we’re hitting we want to have the confidence to take aggressive but controlled swings and hunting a specific zone is something that really free’d me up to do that in my career, unfortunately by the time I started doing this it was too late in my career.

• In pro ball my strength was fastballs in but early in my pro ball career I was trying to cover every pitch in every location. The pitching was simply too good to do this. It led to a lot of swing and miss, lot of K’s barely any walks. It wasn’t until the A’s told me to cut the plate in half and hunt middle in that I started to become more consistent. I finally had a plan that I was confident in and could stick to. This helped me stop expanding the zone & locked me in for my pitch every at bat. Did I still need to cover the outer half with 2 strikes? Yes. But I stopped looking to swing at that outside pitch early in the count because it wasn’t my strength at that point in my career.

• So hitters, find your strengths and create an approach that plays to it. Like me, I think you’ll find much more consistency and confidence at the plate 👏🏼 HUNT YOUR ZONE! (Early in the count and in hitters counts, with 2 strikes you still need to have the ability to protect the whole zone)

#hitting #hittingdrills #hittingcoach #hittingpost #hittingmechanics

HITTERS/COACHES WHAT STANDS OUT?

• What do you see in this swing? The Good? The Bad? Leave a comment and let’s talk hitting!

#hitting #hittingdrills #hittingcoach #hittingpost #hittingmechanics #hittingbombs #hittinggoals

CREATE A ROUTINE‼️

We’ve all heard the old baseball saying that “consistency is key” and it is so true. The players who stick around the longest in this game are the ones who find a way to stay consistent over a long period of time.

Having a daily routine as a hitter is one of the best ways to maintain consistency and confidence at the plate.

This was something I wish I had utilized earlier in my career as a hitter and I highly recommend you start with a daily routine ASAP! Consistency is 🔑💣

#hitting #hittingdrills #hittingmechanics #hittingcoach #hittingbombs #hittingpost #hittinggoals

SLOW 👉🏻 FAST

Sometimes the best thing we can do in the box is SLOW DOWN. In this case I’m referring to our rhythm and timing. 

Every hitter is different and we all have our own rhythm and timing that makes our swing unique and our own. However, sometimes less in more. If we have too much pre pitch movement that isn’t slow and controlled we can tend to hurt our chances of being on time and driving our pitch. 

Rhythm and timing should feel slow and controlled, never rushed, never in a hurry. I loved to think “Slow load, Fast Swing”. I wanted to feel my load as a slow yet powerful movement that propelled me into an extremely quick and powerful swing. For me everything is slow until my front foot hits the ground on my stride, then Boom, we turn it on immediately going into a fast rotation with the body followed by the hands and barrel.

If you’re someone who struggles with consistently being on time, I’d recommend slowing down your rhythm and load. Two seconds was always me target load time. Slow is smooth and smooth is fast. Less is more, BOMBS 💣

Hitting talks 🗣️

• A good load/launch position is essential for creating time and space in the swing to allow good posture to be maintained. 

• In this first swing Max rushed his load a bit leading to a heavier landing on his front side and a forward drift towards the pitch (originally I thought he rushed and cut his stride short but after watching the video I saw he rushed and drifted) which made him lose time in space and go to the “Oh crap” pushback/pullout with the shoulders that we all know too well causing good posture to be lost and a rollover ground ball.

• On the second swing he perfected his load which allowed him to land in a much better position with plenty of time and space to have a clean turn and maintain posture through contact = backspun double in the gap. 

• Moral of the story? Dominate your load, find something that helps you land in a good spot consistently and creates plenty of time and space for a clean turn to contact. I truly believe that 90% of being a good hitter is getting to a good launch position on time 🤙🏻

One year with our sweet Roo

Baby Reese you took us by surprise when you came into this world almost 7 weeks early. We will never forget how scared we were, but all that fear turned to joy the moment we saw you. (Well, most of it. Still can’t believe they let us take you home without giving us a manual first)

Here are some things we’ve learned about you so far.

You seriously dislike things in your face. You love GoGo Squeez pouches. You aren’t a fan of sleeping by yourself. You love playing hide-and-seek. You don’t like being held when there is something exciting to see. You love to laugh. And so much more.

You are funny and so sassy but also sweet and gentle. We are so proud to be your parents sweet baby Roo we love you so much. Happy Birthday ♥️
